{
  "texts": [
    "The landscape gets further complicated if we also consider the social, psychological, and cognitive dimensions, e.g., how ethical behavior is intertwined with the empathy, emotions, and reasoning of embodied agents, and carried out by highly distributed and parallel cognitive systems (Newen et al. 2018; FeldmanHall and Mobbs 2015).",
    "Far from being 'fixed', moral behavior is something which is developed and actively refined through experience.",
    "12 Beyond individuals, ethics is also manifested at the level of societies and culture; maintained and transformed through practices and institutions, mediated through the language of ideology and religion, and with justifications that ranges from divine authority (e.g., word of God), maintaining political order (Hobbes 1651), to the promotion of liberty (Mill 1859) or justice (Rawls 1971).",
    "Hence, to delimit our investigation, we will focus on the complexity of ethical problems as they have been framed within the field of machine ethics.",
    "The majority of technical work in machine ethics has been focusing on normative ethics, or more specifically, how certain tenets or aspects of a normative theory can be implemented so that an artificial agent acts in accordance with the theory (Cervantes et al. 2020; Tolmeijer et al. 2020)."
  ]
}